======================== DOCKER SWARM NOTES ========================

---------------------------------- DEFINITION ----------------------------------

Docker Swarm is a built-in container orchestration tool in Docker used to
manage and run containers across multiple machines (nodes) as a cluster.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

------------------------------- WHAT IT DOES -----------------------------------

- Creates cluster of multiple nodes ✅
- Manages container deployment ✅
- Supports scaling (replicas) ✅
- Provides load balancing ✅
- Ensures high availability ✅
- Automatically replaces failed containers ✅

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

-------------------------------- ARCHITECTURE ----------------------------------

Swarm Cluster consists of:

1. Manager Node:
- Controls entire cluster ✅
- Schedules containers ✅

2. Worker Node:
- Runs containers ✅
- Executes tasks from manager ✅

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

------------------------------- KEY CONCEPTS -----------------------------------

1. Node:
- Machine (EC2 instance)
- Can be Manager or Worker

2. Service:
- Defines application
- Maintains desired state (replicas)

3. Task:
- A running container inside a service

4. Cluster:
- Group of nodes managed together

5. Overlay Network:
- Enables communication between nodes

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

--------------------------- IMPORTANT BEHAVIOR ---------------------------------

- Swarm distributes containers across nodes ✅
- Load balancing is automatic ✅
- Self-healing: failed containers restarted ✅
- Existing containers are NOT rebalanced automatically ❗
- All nodes MUST have access to the image ✅

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

--------------------------------- COMMANDS -------------------------------------

Initialize swarm (manager):
docker swarm init

Leave swarm:
docker swarm leave --force

Get worker join token:
docker swarm join-token worker

Get manager join token:
docker swarm join-token manager

Join worker node:
docker swarm join --token <token> <manager-ip>:2377

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

-------------------------------- NODE COMMANDS ---------------------------------

List all nodes (manager only):
docker node ls

Inspect node:
docker node inspect <node-id>

Change node availability:
docker node update --availability active <node-id>

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

------------------------------ SERVICE COMMANDS --------------------------------

Create service:
docker service create --name myservice -p 3000:3000 myimage

Create with replicas:
docker service create --name myservice --replicas 3 myimage

List services:
docker service ls

View service details:
docker service ps myservice

Scale service:
docker service scale myservice=5

Remove service:
docker service rm myservice

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

------------------------------ CONTAINER VIEW ----------------------------------

View containers on current node:
docker ps

From manager (see distribution):
docker service ps myservice

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------- COMMON ISSUES -------------------------------------

1. Containers only run on manager:
- Worker not active OR
- Image not available on worker

2. "No such image" error:
- Image not present on worker node ❗
- Fix: push image to Docker Hub ✅

3. Join failed:
- Port 2377 blocked ❗
- Use correct IP + open ports ✅

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

---------------------------- REQUIRED PORTS ------------------------------------

2377 → cluster management ✅
7946 → node communication ✅ (TCP + UDP)
4789 → overlay networking ✅ (UDP)

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

----------------------------- COMPLETE FLOW ------------------------------------

1. Install Docker on all nodes ✅
2. Initialize swarm on manager ✅
3. Join worker nodes ✅
4. Create service ✅
5. Scale replicas ✅
6. Swarm distributes containers ✅

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

----------------------------- EXAMPLE FLOW -------------------------------------

docker swarm init

docker swarm join --token <token> <manager-ip>:2377

docker service create --name myservice --replicas 3 myapp:v1

docker service ps myservice

docker service scale myservice=5

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

------------------------------- ONE LINE MEMORY --------------------------------

Swarm = Docker + clustering + scaling ✅

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

-------------------------- COMPOSE vs SWARM ------------------------------------

Docker Compose:
- Single machine ✅
- Local development ✅
- No clustering ❌

Docker Swarm:
- Multiple nodes ✅
- Production capable ✅
- Scaling + load balancing ✅

